"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771237","Department of Health","false","2017-10-30","<p>There are no plans to publish such analyses.</p><p> </p><p>The Government holds NHS England and NHS Improvement to account for delivery of the referral to treatment and other performance targets and patient access standards. Delivery of the standards is impacted by a number of factors such as levels of demand, productivity and financial resources. NHS England has set these out in their Next Steps on the NHS Five Year Forward View, which charts practical and realistic steps for the next few years with the aim of delivering real improvements in patient care and outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2017/18 sets a clear expectation that NHS England will meet agreed standards on accident and emergency, ambulances, diagnostics and referral to treatment.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL2033","2017-10-30T16:37:54.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771237/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771237/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-16","NHS: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will publish their analysis of the cost of achieving the NHS's performance targets and patient access standards.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771238","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>We would expect PCCs and Chief Constables to regularly discuss policing within the force area and funding, however the decision on whether to police a protest is an operational one for the Chief Constable. This is set out in statute in paragraphs 30-33 of the Policing Protocol Order 2011.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T14:56:34.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771238/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771238/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Fracking: Lancashire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Lancashire Police and Crime Commissioner has the power to instruct the Chief Constable to suspend, or scale back, the policing operation at the Cuadrilla site until such time as additional funding is provided by the Home Office.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771239","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>It is not our policy to release details of a Special Grant funding application whilst it is under consideration.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T14:56:54.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771239/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771239/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Fracking: Lancashire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will publish a detailed breakdown of the request for an additional £3.1 million from Lancashire Police for policing the Cuadrilla site.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771240","Home Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>Special Grant funding only covers additional costs. In general this may include staff overtime, mutual aid and rest day working costs. Vehicle or equipment hire costs may also be claimed.</p><p> </p><p>Detailed guidance on Special Grant funding is on the Government website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-funding-special-grant-guidance/special-grant-guidance#home-office-guidance-for-special-grant-funding" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-funding-special-grant-guidance/special-grant-guidance#home-office-guidance-for-special-grant-funding</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-26T16:53:55.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771240/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771240/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Fracking: Protest","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether chief police officers can apply for additional funding to cover the opportunity costs of officers being present at an anti-fracking protest, rather than doing regular community policing duties, or whether such additional funding only covers costs such as unusual overtime and mutual aid.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771241","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-30","<p>The government is proposing an implementation period of around two years. The detail of interim arrangements will be a matter for negotiation.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-10-30T16:07:12.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771241/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771241/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-16","Common Agricultural Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Prime Minister’s proposal for a two-year post-Article 50 implementation period includes continued participation in the Common Agricultural Policy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL2042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771242","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-23","<p>We are working towards achieving the best possible deal for the UK’s food and drink industry, and we want to secure a deep and comprehensive Free-Trade Agreement as an alternative to membership of the Single Market.</p><p>We want to see trade that is as frictionless as possible, including for agricultural and fisheries products.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2044","2017-10-23T12:30:04.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771242/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771242/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-16","Agricultural Products: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of the UK's future relationship with the EU, they will seek preferential access to the EU Single Market for agricultural products.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL2043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771243","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-23","<p>We are working towards achieving the best possible deal for the UK’s food and drink industry, and we want to secure a deep and comprehensive Free-Trade Agreement as an alternative to membership of the Single Market.</p><p>We want to see trade that is as frictionless as possible, including for agricultural and fisheries products.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2043","2017-10-23T12:30:04.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771243/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771243/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-16","Fish Products: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of the UK's future relationship with the EU, they will seek preferential access to the EU Single Market for fisheries products.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL2044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771244","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-30","<p>UK fishing vessels will need to comply with the North Sea Multiannual Plan when fishing in EU waters, both while the UK is still within the EU and when fishing in EU waters in accordance with any agreement post exit. The UK Government will continue to have a strong interest in the overall status and effective long-term management of mixed demersal species and nephrops in the whole North Sea area. The science-based framework established under the Multiannual Plan will provide a valuable support to continued cooperation between the UK and the EU, where it will be important to find a shared basis to agree on sustainable rates of exploitation across all commercially important species. The exact basis for such cooperation is still to be determined.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-10-30T16:26:07.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771244/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771244/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-16","Fisheries: North Sea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, as part of the UK's future relationship with the EU, they will seek to continue participating in the North Sea multiannual plan.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL2045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771245","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-30","<p>It is essential that measures on Client Money Protection are considered in the round and implemented in a sensible and coherent way with other changes to the sector, notably the ban on letting agent fees paid by tenants, and regulation of letting agents.</p><p>We will provide more information on legislation and implementation shortly.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-10-30T14:56:37.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771245/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771245/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Client Money Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 28 March (HL Deb, col 466), when they expect to legislate to introduce compulsory client money protection for landlords and tenants.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771246","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-30","<p>We sought views on how the ban should be implemented and enforced during an eight week public consultation, which closed on 2 June. We received more than 4,700 responses, which we have been analysing carefully.</p><p>We will be publishing our response to the consultation and the Tenant Fees Bill shortly. We will provide more information on the implementation timetable following scrutiny of the draft bill.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-10-30T17:27:50.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771246/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771246/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they expect to legislate to ban letting agents fees.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771247","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government Annual Report and Accounts 2016/17 sets out the activities of the department across the financial year. This was published on 30 June 2017 and includes budget information about Help to Buy and Affordable Homes against total departmental budget. This is available (attached) online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017</a></p><p>For <strong>Help to Buy, </strong>the total budget for each financial year 2011/12 – 2015/16 is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Budget for each financial year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong> <strong>(£m)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong> <strong>(£m)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong> <strong>(£m)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong> <strong>(£m)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong> <strong>(£m)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Help to Buy</strong> <strong>(including First Buy)</strong></p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>142</p></td><td><p>908</p></td><td><p>1,469</p></td><td><p>1,505</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>For <strong>affordable housing</strong>, including social housing, the government funds this through the Affordable Homes programme with bidding for funding being made at beginning of the process. It does not announce funding on a yearly basis.</p><p>The expanded programme is fully flexible allowing a wider range of products that will help meet the housing needs of a wider range of people in different circumstances, including Help to Buy, Shared Ownership, Rent to Buy as well as affordable rent and social rent.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-01T14:16:21.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771247/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771247/answer","171101 DCLG Annual Report and Account 2016 -17  - HL2048.pdf","Annual report and accounts 2016 - 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771247/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what percentage of new funding announced for housing in each year since June 2010 has been targeted towards (1) social housing,  (2) affordable housing, and (3) Help to Buy, Rent to Buy and other similar schemes.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771248","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-30","<p>Licensing is an effective targeted tool delivering improved standards and safety in the private rented sector in specific areas that are suffering from serious problems. The Department will shortly undertake a review of selective licensing.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-10-30T17:27:02.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771248/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771248/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Landlords: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of local authority private sector landlord licensing schemes.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771249","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>Provisions 80-91 on rents for high income social tenants have formally been dropped.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-11-01T17:42:54.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771249/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771249/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what measures provided for in or under the Housing and Planning Act 2016 have been formally dropped.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771250","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-30","<p>We are taking stock of the extension of Right to Buy discounts to housing association tenants, and will announce more details in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-10-30T14:57:04.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771250/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771250/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what progress they are making on extending Right to Buy to housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL2051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771251","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union, working with officials across Government, is undertaking a wide range of analysis covering the entirety of the UK economy in order to support negotiations. Both parties want to achieve the best possible outcome and the strongest possible partnership for the future - one that works for the UK and for the EU.</p><p>As Parliament has agreed, we will not publish anything that would undermine our ability to negotiate the best deal for the United Kingdom. It is not standard practice to provide an ongoing commentary on internal analytical work that is being carried out within government.</p><p>We are confident that a future partnership between the UK and EU is in the interests of both sides, so we approach these negotiations anticipating success. We do not want or expect a no deal outcome. However, a responsible government should prepare for all potential outcomes, including the unlikely scenario in which no mutually satisfactory agreement can be reached.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-10-23T11:51:01.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771251/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771251/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-16","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any sectoral advice papers which they commissioned in relation to Brexit will be released in 2017 in order to assist public and business assessments of the economic and social implications of the UK's departure from the EU without the conclusion of arrangements on Northern Ireland, financial arrangements with the EU, the status of UK and EU citizens, the jurisdiction of the European Court of Justice, and a comprehensive trade framework.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL2052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771252","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office premises may be used by non-governmental bodies for events that are in line with Government policy, as in this case.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-30T16:04:42.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771252/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771252/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Non-governmental Organisations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have changed the rules which prevent non-governmental bodies from using government premises for non-governmental purposes; and if no change in the rules has been made, why the launch of the non-governmental Initiative for Free Trade was allowed to take place in the Map Room of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in early October.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL2053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771253","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-30","<p>The International Monetary Fund’s report conclusions consider the OECD as a whole and are not specifically aimed at the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The UK already has a progressive system. The income tax system consists of three progressive rates of tax – 20%, 40% and 45%, which sit above an internationally high tax-free personal allowance. As a result the top 1% of income taxpayers pay 28% of all income tax and HMRC statistics show additional rate taxpayers paid £46.7bn of tax in 2014-15 compared with £34.5bn in 2010-11.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-30T16:20:13.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771253/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771253/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-16","Income Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their assessment of the October International Monetary Fund half-yearly fiscal monitor report view that tax systems should have become more progressive to reduce inequality and that there is now "scope for increasing the progressivity of income taxation without significantly hurting growth".","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL2054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771254","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Meetings of the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations) are subject to agreement by all four administrations. JMC(EN) met most recently on 16 October and agreed to meet again before Christmas.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-10-30T16:17:29.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771254/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771254/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what date has been agreed for the next meeting of the Joint Ministerial Committee on EU negotiations; and what is the frequency of meetings intended for the future.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL2055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771255","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-30","<p>The principal aim of the youth justice system is to prevent offending by children and young people. Since the peak in youth proven offending in 2006/07, the average number of under-18s in youth custody has decreased by 70% from 2,915 to 869 in 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>The sentencing framework for young people provides for robust alternatives to custody in the form of community-based sentences: referral orders and youth rehabilitation orders (including youth rehabilitation orders with intensive supervision and surveillance). Custody should always be a measure of last resort and be the shortest term commensurate with the seriousness of the offence. The main custodial sentence for children and young people, the Detention and Training Order, is not available for children under 12 years old and any case that warrants one of less than four months must result in a non‑custodial sentence.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-10-30T17:11:45.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771255/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771255/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-16","Youth Custody","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to reduce the number of children and young people in custody on the prison estate.","false","Biography information for Lord Laming",,"Lord Laming","HL2056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771256","Department for Education","false","2017-10-27","<p>We are clear that the right care placements for looked after children are vital for their stability, and these decisions should assess the risk of children going missing from placements. The Government’s ‘Missing Children and Adults strategy’ focuses primarily on vulnerable people who go missing within England and Wales, and provides a clear core framework in which we can work with local councils, police and other local partners to deliver collectively, the best protection possible for missing children, adults and their families.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s 2014 statutory guidance on ‘Children who run away or go missing from home or care’, makes clear the expectations we have on local councils to work with police and other partners to safeguard all vulnerable children. In addition, since 2014, we have placed a duty on local councils to report all incidences of children going missing from care. Children’s homes must have policies to stop children going missing; and when children do go missing, they must respond in line with local police protocols that includes understanding patterns of missing episodes to put preventative steps in place.</p><p> </p><p>Local councils are continuing to improve data collections to include all incidents of children missing from care and so the numbers recorded are increasing as would be expected (although the data is still categorised as experimental). We will continue to assess data quality and what this indicates about managing risk.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-27T11:03:16.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771256/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771256/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Runaway Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to prevent children in the care of local authorities from going missing.","false","Biography information for Lord Laming",,"Lord Laming","HL2057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771257","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>The enforcement powers of the Equality and Human Rights Commission are set out in sections 20 to 32 of the Equality Act 2006, as amended by the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013. The Commission can investigate an unlawful act (section 20); issue an unlawful act notice (section 21); apply to a court for an action plan from a person served with an unlawful act notice (section 22); seek an injunction where necessary (section 24); provide legal assistance to an individual who is or may become party to legal proceedings (section 28); initiate or intervene in judicial review proceedings (section 30); and issue a compliance notice where it thinks that a public authority has failed to comply with the public sector equality duty (section 32).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-30T17:10:29.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771257/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771257/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Equality Act 2010","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the remarks by Baroness Vere of Norbiton on 16 October, whether the Equality and Human Rights Commission has the power to enforce the Equality Act 2010 in the civil courts where it considers the law has been breached.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771258","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Papers for meetings of the Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary) and the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotations) are subject to agreement by all administrations. Once agreed, papers are circulated to attendees by the JMC joint secretariat consisting of officials of all four administrations.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-10-30T16:24:14.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771258/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771258/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Joint Ministerial Committee","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how far in advance they aim to circulate papers to those attending meetings of (1) the Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary), and (2) the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations).","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL2059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771259","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Meetings of the Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary) and the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations) are subject to agreement by all four Administrations. JMC(EN) met most recently on 16 October and agreed to meet again before Christmas.</p><p>The Memorandum of Understanding agreed between the UK Government and Devolved Administrations states that the Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary) should meet at least once a year. The UK Government and the Devolved Administrations will work together to agree any future date of the next Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary).</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-10-30T17:32:22.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771259/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771259/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Joint Ministerial Committee","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many meetings of (1) the Joint Ministerial Committee (Plenary), and (2) the Joint Ministerial Committee (EU Negotiations), they intend to convene in 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL2060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771260","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>Work on the annual report of the Joint Ministerial Committee is currently being taken forward by representatives of the UK Government and each of the devolved administrations, and is expected to be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-10-30T16:26:44.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771260/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771260/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Devolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to their response dated 17 January to the report from the Constitution Committee Inter-governmental relations in the United Kingdom (Session 2014–15, HL Paper 146), when their report on inter-governmental relations will be published.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL2061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771261","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>The UK is committed to strengthening the links between the Overseas Territories and the Commonwealth. As membership of the Commonwealth is limited to sovereign states, the Overseas Territories cannot attend the Heads of Government Meeting or other ministerial meetings in their own right but will be represented by the UK. The UK Government will discuss the four policy pillars for the summit (security, sustainability, fairness and prosperity), with the Overseas Territories ahead of next year’s summit, in order to seek their views and feedback.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-30T17:04:19.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771261/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771261/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-16","British Overseas Territories: Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they propose to provide observer status for British Overseas Territories during the Commonwealth Summit in London in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771262","Department for Education","false","2017-10-27","<p>Ministers are currently considering attendance at the Commonwealth Education Ministers Conference in Fiji in February 2018, and a decision will be taken in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-27T11:04:16.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771262/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771262/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Education: Commonwealth","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they propose to send a Minister to represent them at the Commonwealth Education Ministers Conference in Fiji in February 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL2063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771263","Department of Health","false","2017-10-26","<p>Any healthcare professional, including general practitioners (GPs) and consultants, can report an Adverse Drug Reaction (ADR) report concerning a patient via the Yellow Card Scheme (YCS). There are a number of different reporting options available to healthcare professionals, which include the Yellow Card website, Yellow Card app, paper forms that can be sent in via free post, and the Yellow Card free phone. Furthermore, in some clinical settings, integrated IT systems are in place for ADR reporting. This allows healthcare professionals to submit Yellow Cards electronically by populating information from the patient’s electronic health record, including relevant information about their medical condition.</p><p> </p><p>Patients are given the opportunity to provide contact details for their GP or consultant when reporting directly to the YCS. If they choose to provide these details, permission is requested to advise the healthcare professional of the ADR report and/or to follow up for additional information directly with the healthcare professional. If permission is granted, a copy of the report will be sent to the healthcare professional, who can then provide further information on the patient’s medical condition if they wish. When requesting follow-up, the healthcare professional will be prompted as to what information is of interest for the further assessment of the report. Where patients have not provided details or permission to contact a healthcare professional, any further information required concerning the ADR report will be requested from the patient.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-26T10:46:07.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771263/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771263/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-16","Drugs: Side Effects","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Medicine and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency accepts medical correspondence from GPs or consultants about a patient's medical condition with a Yellow Card report.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771264","Department of Health","false","2017-10-25","<p>All new vaccines that are to be marketed in the United Kingdom require a Marketing Authorisation issued either by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), the UK national competent authority, or by the European Commission.</p><p> </p><p>Applications for Marketing Authorisations for any new medicine, including vaccines, must contain data on the quality, safety and efficacy of the medicinal product. In the case of vaccines, information on the safety and immunogenicity of the antigenic components of the candidate vaccine in the target population must be provided. These data are assessed by MHRA and, where applicable, the European Medicines Agency. This information is fully evaluated to establish the efficacy and safety of the medicinal product, and to ensure that the balance of the expected benefits and potential risks is favourable. Safety evaluation of vaccines continues in the post-licensing period and throughout the life-cycle of the product.</p><p> </p><p>An independent external review of the authorisation of new medicines, including vaccines, is provided by the Commission on Human Medicines and its Expert Advisory Groups, which advises the MHRA and Ministers on the safety, efficacy and quality of medicinal products. The members of the Commission are appointed by Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), another independent expert advisory committee and statutory body, advises the Government on matters relating to vaccination and immunisation. The JCVI advises the Government on all changes to the national vaccination programme, including on the introduction of new vaccines. The JCVI reviews evidence on the potential health benefits and the safety of vaccines when developing its advice. The JCVI keeps all UK vaccination programmes under review, including regular updates from the MHRA on vaccine associated adverse events reported in the UK.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-25T15:01:07.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771264/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771264/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-16","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how the risks and benefits of new vaccinations are assessed; and who is responsible for that assessment.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771265","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Government has made no assessment of the usage of cycle lanes in the London congestion charge area.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-10-25T11:40:06.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771265/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771265/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Cycleways: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the usage of cycle lanes in the London congestion charge area between the hours of 10am and 4pm during weekdays.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771266","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Government provides funding to Transport for London (TfL) via the Greater London Authority. It is the responsibility of the Mayor to determine how TfL’s budget should be spent and for him to decide what to prioritise.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-10-25T11:40:21.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771266/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771266/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Cycleways: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much money they have provided for the construction and maintenance of cycle lanes in the London congestion charge areas in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL2067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771267","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-25","<p>Transport in London is devolved to the Mayor of London, and it is for him to consider what, if any, assessment is made of the impacts of cycle lanes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any assessment of the impact of the cycle lanes on congestion in London congestion charge areas and the implications for the environment.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-10-25T11:40:39.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771267/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771267/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Cycleways: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the cycle lanes on congestion in London congestion charge areas and the implications for the environment.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawson",,"Lord Mawson","HL2068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771268","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-23","<p>As my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy set out in his statement to Parliament on 10 October 2017, Ministers and senior officials across government have had extensive engagement with the government of the United States regarding this trade dispute. The total of significant interaction amounts to twenty-five calls and meetings. This includes with senior members of the US Administration and Congress.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has discussed the matter a number of times with President Trump, stressing the importance of Bombardier’s operations in Belfast and asking the US Government to do all they can to encourage Boeing to drop its complaint. Cabinet Ministers, including the Business Secretary, Foreign Secretary, Defence Secretary, Chancellor of the Exchequer, Trade Secretary and the Northern Ireland Secretary, have reinforced the UK’s serious concerns with, among others, the US Secretary of Commerce, the US Secretary of State, the US Treasury Secretary, the US Trade Representative and other members of the US Administration, as well as the EU Trade Commissioner.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-10-23T11:40:59.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771268/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771268/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-16","Bombardier: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many interactions, and with which officials, have they had with the government of the United States regarding the trade dispute brought by Boeing against Bombardier.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771269","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-31","<p>The Government discusses trade issues with the US on a regular basis, including through the UK-US Trade and Investment Working Group. UK and EU officials have also discussed tariff rate quotas (TRQs) with the US and other counterparts in Geneva. These discussions cover, among other things, data and methodologies, for apportioning tariff-rate quotas. The Government’s dialogue with the World Trade Organization (WTO) Membership is ongoing. We will work closely with the EU and other WTO members, to ensure a simple, fair, and transparent transition for all parties that minimises disruption to our trading relationships. It is the Government's intention to respect and preserve existing rights and commitments in the WTO.</p><p>It should also be noted that the UK is a full and founding member of the WTO and already has schedules which it shares at present with the EU Member States.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2017-10-31T16:15:31.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771269/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771269/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-16","Import Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions the Prime Minister has had with the President of the United States regarding the agreement between the EU and the UK about how to split the EU's existing tariff rate quotas under the shared schedule at the World Trade Organisation.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL2070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771270","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-30","<p>The government’s economic objective is to achieve strong, sustainable and balanced growth. To this end, the government’s economic strategy consists of: operationally independent monetary and macroprudential policy responsible for maintaining price and financial stability and supporting the economy; credible fiscal policy with the flexibility to support the economy; and structural reforms to address long-term economic weaknesses.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-30T16:20:48.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771270/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771270/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-16","Economic Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the policy options available to HM Treasury and the Bank of England in the event of a sharp slowdown in the UK's economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771271","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Bank of England Act 1998 established that the objectives of the Monetary Policy Committee of the Bank of England are to maintain price stability and, subject to that, to support the economic policy of the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor reaffirmed at the Spring Budget 2017 that the committee will continue to target 2 per cent inflation as defined by the 12-month increase in the consumer prices index.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-30T16:21:09.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771271/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771271/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-16","Inflation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have recently considered setting a temporary or permanent increase in the inflation target set for the Monetary Policy Committee.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771272","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>There have been over 1.1 million apprenticeship starts since May 2015 and the Government remains committed to reaching 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. The Government has introduced the Apprenticeship Levy to provide sustainable investment in high quality apprenticeships, and by 2020 apprenticeship funding in England will be £2.45 billion, which is double than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is monitoring the number of apprenticeship starts as these changes take effect. Ultimately, it is too early to draw conclusions on the impact of these reforms before employers have had time to adjust. However, the Government will continue to oversee the apprenticeship program to ensure its success.</p><p> </p><p>These reforms to apprenticeships are the biggest changes the Government has ever made in this area, and include the introduction of the Apprenticeship Levy and new funding arrangements in April and May respectively. As a result, the Government expects a period of adjustment for employers wanting to explore the opportunities such reforms offer. Employers have 24 months to spend their levy funds.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL2074","2017-10-30T17:53:05.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771272/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771272/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the causatory factors leading to a decline in the number of young people starting an apprenticeship in the current year; and how that decline will affect their target to create three million apprenticeships by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771273","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>There have been over 1.1 million apprenticeship starts since May 2015 and the Government remains committed to reaching 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. The Government has introduced the Apprenticeship Levy to provide sustainable investment in high quality apprenticeships, and by 2020 apprenticeship funding in England will be £2.45 billion, which is double than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is monitoring the number of apprenticeship starts as these changes take effect. Ultimately, it is too early to draw conclusions on the impact of these reforms before employers have had time to adjust. However, the Government will continue to oversee the apprenticeship program to ensure its success.</p><p> </p><p>These reforms to apprenticeships are the biggest changes the Government has ever made in this area, and include the introduction of the Apprenticeship Levy and new funding arrangements in April and May respectively. As a result, the Government expects a period of adjustment for employers wanting to explore the opportunities such reforms offer. Employers have 24 months to spend their levy funds.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL2073","2017-10-30T17:53:05.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771273/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771273/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether, in the light of the reduced number of young people starting an apprenticeship in the current year, they have considered withdrawing the apprenticeship levy charged to companies with more than 250 members of staff.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771274","Department of Health","false","2017-10-26","<p>No such assessment has been carried out.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-26T10:46:24.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771274/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771274/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-16","Congenital Abnormalities: Health Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case for introducing a Birth Defects Prevention Month and a Folic Acid Awareness Week similar to those in the United States, and of the potential effects of such a step on public health and the economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771275","Department of Health","false","2017-10-26","<p>The data is not held in the format requested.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-26T10:46:36.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771275/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771275/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-16","Neural Tube Defects","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in each of the last three years, how many pregnancies affected by neural tube defects were second or subsequent pregnancies.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771276","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-10-26T15:07:39.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771276/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771276/answer","HL2077 final.pdf","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771276/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, in the light of official figures published in August showing that the number of international students overstaying their visas was lower than previously estimated by the ONS, what changes have been made to the quarterly net migration statistics.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771277","Home Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>The Government remains committed to bringing net migration down to sustainable levels. It will take time to achieve this. We will manage reforms to the immigration system responsibly so that it continues to serve the national interest.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-26T16:58:56.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771277/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771277/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the probability of reducing non-UK net migration to the tens of thousands prior to Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771278","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>The department is supporting adults in England to ensure they have the English language skills for life and work.</p><p>Adults in England who do not have a Level 2 qualification in English are eligible for free courses up to, and including, Level 2 in English literacy. Adults in England are also eligible for fully or co-funded courses to help them learn English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL), depending on their employment status. Funding is available for ESOL courses and qualifications up to Level 2. In 2016/17, the department supported 536,700 adults to improve their English skills through literacy courses and 114,400 through ESOL courses.</p><p>Since 2013, the Department for Communities and Local Government has invested £12 million to support 54,000 isolated adults to learn English in community settings at pre-entry level, focusing on women with no or very little English who are unlikely to access classes in more formal settings.</p><p>The English language proficiency level for non-UK nationals seeking permanent residency or applying to naturalise as British citizens is set at B1 of the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages. This is equivalent to an ESOL Entry Level 3. Detailed Immigration Rules can be accessed here at the below web link or via the attached document.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/immigration-rules/immigration-rules-appendix-koll" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/immigration-rules/immigration-rules-appendix-koll</a>.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-30T16:33:49.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771278/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771278/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Immigrants: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that UK nationals can meet the English language proficiency threshold that has been set for non-UK nationals seeking permanent residency.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771279","Home Office","false","2017-10-30","<p>There are no plans to enact restrictions on free movement for EU citizens prior to the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p>The Government has repeatedly made clear that until we leave the EU, EU citizens will continue to enjoy the same rights and status, and remain subject to the same residence requirements under EU law, as is currently the case.</p><p>This is set out in our position paper published on 26th June 2017, available at: www.gov.uk/government/publications/safeguarding-the-position-of-eu-citizens-in-the-uk-and-uk-nationals-in-the-eu</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-30T16:04:04.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771279/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771279/answer","HO_EU_Citizen_Rights_Policy_Factsheet_A5_FINAL_WEB_260617_2.pdf","pdf copy of publication - safeguarding position...","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771279/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Immigration: EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to enact restrictions on free movement for EU nationals prior to Brexit; and if so, how.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2080"
