"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771394","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Childcare Choices website brings together all the government’s childcare offers into one place for the first time. It is the starting point for parents to find out about what government support they might be entitled to. Since its launch in March 2017, the website has over 1 million unique visitors. Parents can follow a link from Childcare Choices to the childcare service to apply for 30 hours free childcare and/or Tax-Free Childcare. From Childcare Choices they can also use the Childcare Calculator to work out which offer is best for them.</p><p> </p><p><em>Since the childcare service was launched in April, over 216,000 30 hours eligibility codes were generated for children who will be eligible for 30 hours free childcare in the autumn term, and Tax-Free Childcare accounts have been opened for more than 155,000 children. Whilst the majority of parents have applied with no issue, some parents have experienced difficulties. HMRC have apologised to those parents and are working with National Savings &amp; Investments (and their supplier Atos) to make a range of improvements to the childcare service. HMRC have arrangements in place to ensure that no parents miss out financially as a result of these issues.</em></p><p> </p><p>In relation to the numbers of childcare providers signed-up to deliver Tax-Free Childcare I refer the honorable member to my response to Parliamentary Question (105541) on 16 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>To date, 14% of successful applicants for Tax-Free Childcare are self-employed or have a partner who is self-employed. These are people who would otherwise not have acess to supported childcare.</p><p> </p><p>A study into the feasibility of measuring the impact on the labour and childcare market impacts of Tax-Free Childcare was published in February 2016 and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/feasibility-study-into-evaluating-the-labour-and-childcare-market-impacts-of-tax-free-childcare-and-the-free-early-education-entitlement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/feasibility-study-into-evaluating-the-labour-and-childcare-market-impacts-of-tax-free-childcare-and-the-free-early-education-entitlement</a>. The Government has committed to carry out a post-implementation review, two years after the implementation of Tax-Free Childcare to evaluate the impact of the scheme, including on the childcare market.</p><p> </p><p>The parent application, account and helpline for Tax-Free Childcare are delivered by National Savings &amp; Investments, working their supplier Atos. The arrangements for performance management of National Savings &amp; Investments, including the performance of the childcare service, were described in response to a Parliamentary Question (105683) on 16 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Director General for Transformation at HM Revenue &amp; Customs, provided information on compensation arrangements in a letter to the Chair of the Treasury Select Committee on 4 October, found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Correspondence/2017-19/Correspondence-hmrc-taxfree-childcare-compensation-041017.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Correspondence/2017-19/Correspondence-hmrc-taxfree-childcare-compensation-041017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>As announced at Budget 2016, Employer Supported Childcare schemes will close to new entrants from April 2018.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","107743 ; 107860 ; 107861 ; 107873 ; 107874 ; 107892","2017-10-24T11:39:00.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771394/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771394/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many childcare providers have registered for the provision of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","107862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771395","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Childcare Choices website brings together all the government’s childcare offers into one place for the first time. It is the starting point for parents to find out about what government support they might be entitled to. Since its launch in March 2017, the website has over 1 million unique visitors. Parents can follow a link from Childcare Choices to the childcare service to apply for 30 hours free childcare and/or Tax-Free Childcare. From Childcare Choices they can also use the Childcare Calculator to work out which offer is best for them.</p><p> </p><p><em>Since the childcare service was launched in April, over 216,000 30 hours eligibility codes were generated for children who will be eligible for 30 hours free childcare in the autumn term, and Tax-Free Childcare accounts have been opened for more than 155,000 children. Whilst the majority of parents have applied with no issue, some parents have experienced difficulties. HMRC have apologised to those parents and are working with National Savings &amp; Investments (and their supplier Atos) to make a range of improvements to the childcare service. HMRC have arrangements in place to ensure that no parents miss out financially as a result of these issues.</em></p><p> </p><p>In relation to the numbers of childcare providers signed-up to deliver Tax-Free Childcare I refer the honorable member to my response to Parliamentary Question (105541) on 16 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>To date, 14% of successful applicants for Tax-Free Childcare are self-employed or have a partner who is self-employed. These are people who would otherwise not have acess to supported childcare.</p><p> </p><p>A study into the feasibility of measuring the impact on the labour and childcare market impacts of Tax-Free Childcare was published in February 2016 and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/feasibility-study-into-evaluating-the-labour-and-childcare-market-impacts-of-tax-free-childcare-and-the-free-early-education-entitlement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/feasibility-study-into-evaluating-the-labour-and-childcare-market-impacts-of-tax-free-childcare-and-the-free-early-education-entitlement</a>. The Government has committed to carry out a post-implementation review, two years after the implementation of Tax-Free Childcare to evaluate the impact of the scheme, including on the childcare market.</p><p> </p><p>The parent application, account and helpline for Tax-Free Childcare are delivered by National Savings &amp; Investments, working their supplier Atos. The arrangements for performance management of National Savings &amp; Investments, including the performance of the childcare service, were described in response to a Parliamentary Question (105683) on 16 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Director General for Transformation at HM Revenue &amp; Customs, provided information on compensation arrangements in a letter to the Chair of the Treasury Select Committee on 4 October, found here:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Correspondence/2017-19/Correspondence-hmrc-taxfree-childcare-compensation-041017.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/treasury/Correspondence/2017-19/Correspondence-hmrc-taxfree-childcare-compensation-041017.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>As announced at Budget 2016, Employer Supported Childcare schemes will close to new entrants from April 2018.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","107743 ; 107860 ; 107861 ; 107862 ; 107874 ; 107892","2017-10-24T11:39:00.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771395/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771395/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the technical performance of the Childcare Choices portal and the effect of that performance on access to (a) 30 free hours and (b) tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","107873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771396","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>My Department has made no such assessment. The National Planning Policy Framework sets out the need to create safe and accessible environments where crime and disorder, and the fear of crime, do not undermine quality of life or community cohesion.</p><p>Planning Practice Guidance provides further advice on how to design out crime and design in community safety and that this should be central to the planning and delivery of new development.</p><p>The prevention of crime and the enhancement of community safety are matters that a local authority should consider when exercising its planning functions under the Town and Country Planning legislation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:22:47.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771396/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771396/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Burglary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential connection between (a) street and (b) ambient lighting and the incidence of burglaries.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771397","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-24","<p>Estimates of new build dwellings starts for England and in each local authority district, to June Quarter 2017, are shown in Live Table 253a at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-house-building</a></p><p>Data are collected as quarterly totals from local authorities and independent approved inspectors, so monthly estimates are not available centrally. Data for the September Quarter 2017 is scheduled for publication on the 30 November 2017.</p><p>These cover new build dwellings only. The Department also publishes an annual release entitled ‘Housing supply: net additional dwellings, England’, which is the primary and most comprehensive measure of the total change in housing supply. These figures are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-supply-net-additional-dwellings-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-supply-net-additional-dwellings-england-2015-to-2016</a></p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-24T15:36:28.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771397/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771397/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing Starts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many housing starts there were in (a) May, (b) June, (c) July and (d) August 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771398","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>There are no central government records kept on waiting lists for allotments.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:14:48.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771398/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771398/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Allotments: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of people on a waiting list for an allotment in England in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771399","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government provided funding totalling £9.7 million in 2015/16 and £11.2 million in 2016/17 to a range of organisations delivering projects and activity to help create more integrated communities. Within those totals, the following grants were provided to support organisations or activities with a significant faith element.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16 (£000s)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17 (£000s)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Anne Frank Trust UK</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>84</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Board of Deputies of British Jews</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Faith Matters</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>504</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fayre Share Foundation</p></td><td><p>125</p></td><td><p>175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Holocaust Memorial Day Trust</p></td><td><p>980</p></td><td><p>980</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Inter Faith Network for the United Kingdom</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>305</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MITZVAH DAY 365</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Church Urban Fund</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td><td><p>1,960</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ummah Help</p></td><td><p>333</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wiener Library</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-07T13:49:56.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771399/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771399/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Community Relations: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what grants his Department has made to which (a) Muslim, (b) Jewish, (c) Christian and (d) inter-faith organisations for the purposes of integration and community cohesion in each year since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771400","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-01","<p>We do not commission external research on citizenship or public attitudes towards extremism, although we do consider academic work, that produced by think tanks and trusted community organisations as well as that provided by the Home Office’s Research, Information and Communications Unit (RICU) and by the Extremism Analysis Unit. We have also published some data from the Citizenship Survey relating to this topic between July 2010 and September 2011.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-01T15:19:00.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771400/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771400/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Radicalism: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research his Department has (a) commissioned and (b) published since May 2010 on citizenship and public attitudes towards extremism.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771401","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Home Office leads on Counter-Extremism policy within Government. My Department leads on integration and has published 'Creating the Conditions for Integration' in February 2012, which set out the Government 's approach to integration.</p><p>On 5 December 2016, Dame Louise Casey published her independent report: 'A Review into Opportunity and Integration'. Since then my Department has been reviewing the available evidence on the main causes of poor integration.</p><p>In the coming months we will bring forward plans for tackling these issues through a new integration strategy.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-24T14:27:55.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771401/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771401/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department has provided directly to the public to help it understand the threat from extremism and to promote integration; and whether such information has been made available in languages other than English.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771402","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Ministry of Justice is finalising a post implementation review of the 2014 bailiff law reforms. We will make a decision on publication in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-23T16:42:00.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771402/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771402/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-16","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to review the effect on households of the 2014 changes to enforcement agents.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","107883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771403","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>Under the Housing Act 2004 landlords letting their properties under Assured Shorthold Tenancies must protect their tenant’s deposit in one of three government authorised schemes.</p><p>Landlords who fail to comply with the statutory requirements are liable for a mandatory financial penalty of between one and three times the amount of the deposit, payable to the tenant, on the tenant bringing proceedings to the County Court under section 214 of the Housing Act 2004. Non-compliance also affects Landlords' ability to rely on Section 21 of the Housing Act 1988.</p><p>The landlord must protect the deposit in one of the schemes within 30 calendar days from the day the deposit is received and must provide the tenant with details (Prescribed Information) of how their deposit has been protected within the same 30 day period.</p><p>In many cases, the landlord will enter into a contractual arrangement with a letting agent which allows the agent to carry out these duties on the landlord’s behalf. However, it is the landlord who remains responsible for carrying out these statutory obligations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-23T16:12:25.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771403/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771403/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department has taken to establish the role of letting agents in ensuring that landlords comply with their obligation to protect tenants' monies in tenancy deposit schemes.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","107887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771404","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>We have been clear that building owners are responsible for funding fire safety measures, but councils should contact us if they have any concerns about funding fire safety works. Government will consider financial flexibilities for local authorities who need to undertake essential fire safety work to make a building safe.</p><p>32 local authorities have contacted the Department regarding work to ensure fire safety in tower blocks. We have not rejected any requests for support for essential works to make a building fire safe, and will consider further from local authorities as they provide it.</p><p>Housing associations that are concerned about their ability to meet these costs should contact the Social Housing Regulator. So far, no housing associations have contacted the Regulator with concerns about their financial viability as a result of having to meet these costs.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-23T16:10:29.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771404/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771404/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","High Rise Flats: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many requests his Department has received from (a) local authorities, (b) housing associations and (c) other social housing providers for financial support to fit sprinkler systems in high-rise tower blocks since the Grenfell Tower fire; and what his Department's response was to each of those requests.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","107921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771405","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Figures on the age of fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0503 at the link below.</p><p>Figures on the source of ignition causing fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0602 at the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","107797 ; 107798","2017-10-24T15:34:20.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771405/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771405/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Private Rented Housing: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people aged (a) 0 to 10, (b) 11 to 20, (c) 21 to 30, (d) 31 to 40, (e) 41 to 50, (f) 51 to 60, (g) 61 to 70, (h) 71 to 80, (i) 81 to 90 and (j) over 91 years who (i) died and (ii) were injured as a result of fire in private rented sector housing in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771406","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-24","<p>My Department has no separate budget for catering and hospitality.</p><p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to Question UIN 69215 on 25 April 2017. Spending figures for catering and hospitality for the period 2016-17 amounted to £9,822, down from £456,142 in 2009-10.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-24T14:28:24.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771406/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771406/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Department for Communities and Local Government: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's (a) catering and (b) hospitality budget was in (i) 2015, (ii) 2016 and (iii) 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771407","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>Each year, the Department’s English Housing Survey collects and publishes information about whether homes have working smoke alarms. The following link gives number and proportion of homes with at least one working smoke alarm, by tenure, for the last three years for which data are available: English Housing Survey 2015-16 Headline Report, Annex Table 2.16, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-headline-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-headline-report</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-23T16:11:26.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771407/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771407/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing: Smoke Alarms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number and proportion of (a) privately-rented, (b) social and (c) owner-occupied homes in England which had at least one working smoke alarm in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771408","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-24","<p>The information below is current as of 30 September 2017.</p><p>Women in Top posts (Senior Civil Service Grade):</p><p>1. 50 (54.9 per cent) Female</p><p>Whole of DCLG</p><p>1. 779 (51.1 per cent) Female</p><p>2. 206 (18.6 per cent) BAME*</p><p>3. 82 (7.4 per cent) Disabled*</p><p>*percentage figures for BAME and Disabled do not include employees who have not declared their status.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-24T14:29:11.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771408/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771408/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of his Department's staff excluding non-departmental public bodies were (a) women in top management posts, (b) women, (c) black and minority ethnic and (d) disabled in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771409","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>It is for local authorities to consider changes to the Green Belt. Only in exceptional circumstances may a local authority alter its Green Belt, by means of the Local Plan process. Local authorities are expected to report any Green Belt boundary change found to be justified, to inform the Local Authority Green Belt Statistics that we publish annually. From the statistics available for past years, the figures are set out in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total declassified area (hectares)</p></td><td><p>Total classified area (hectares)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>850</p></td><td><p>460</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>540</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>1,980</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>1,030</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>790</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>- = negligible (fewer than five hectares)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures included in the table are the rounded sum of unrounded values and therefore may not sum to the net changes published in the statistical releases of each year.</p><p>These figures are based on changes published in each year’s statistical release and do not reflect any subsequent revisions.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-23T16:08:07.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771409/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771409/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many hectares of land in England have been (a) declassified and (b) classified as greenbelt in each of the last 20 years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771410","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-07","<p>a) England figures for the percentage of housing built on Green Belt land for each calendar year from 1989 to 2011 inclusive are available in live table P246 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267566/201312_-_Tables_P243-P246_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_the_Green_Belt.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267566/201312_-_Tables_P243-P246_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_the_Green_Belt.xls</a></p><p>England figures for the percentage of housing built on Green Belt land for each financial year from 2013-14 to 2015-16 inclusive are available in live table P310 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx</a>. They are based on a different methodology from those for 2011 and earlier years and so are not directly comparable.</p><p>b) England figures for the percentage of housing built on previously-developed land for each calendar year from 1989 to 2011 inclusive are available in live table P211 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267562/201312_-_Tables_P211-P213_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_Previously_Developed_Land.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267562/201312_-_Tables_P211-P213_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_Previously_Developed_Land.xls</a></p><p>England figures for the percentage of housing built on previously developed land for each financial year from 2013-14 to 2015-16 inclusive are available in live table P300 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx</a>. They are based on a different methodology from those for 2011 and earlier years and so are not directly comparable.</p><p>The attached table provides estimated numbers of housing units built on (i) Green Belt and ii) previously-developed land in the last 20 years.</p><p>a) The number of hectares of Green Belt land used for housing in each calendar year from 1989 to 2011 inclusive are available in live table P246 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267566/201312_-_Tables_P243-P246_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_the_Green_Belt.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267566/201312_-_Tables_P243-P246_-_LUCS_-_Changes_on_the_Green_Belt.xls</a></p><p>The number of hectares of Green Belt land used for housing in each financial year from 2013-14 to 2015-16 inclusive are available in live table P382 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx</a>. They are based on a different methodology from those for 2011 and earlier years and so are not directly comparable.</p><p>b) The number of hectares of previously-developed land used for housing in each calendar year from 1989 to 2011 inclusive are available in live table P226 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267563/201312_-_Tables_P221-P226_-_LUCS_-_Land_changing_to_residential_use.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/267563/201312_-_Tables_P221-P226_-_LUCS_-_Land_changing_to_residential_use.xls</a></p><p>The number of hectares of previously-developed land used for housing in each financial year from 2013-14 to 2015-16 inclusive are available in live table P371 at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/595736/1516_Land_Use_Change_Statistics_Live_Tables_Feb_revision.xlsx</a>. They are based on a different methodology from those for 2011 and earlier years and so are not directly comparable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-11-07T16:42:51.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771410/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771410/answer","Question UIN 107804 table - estimated numbers of housing units.xlsx","Table - estimated number of housing units","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771410/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of housing development has taken place on (a) greenbelt and (b) brownfield land in each of the last 20 years in England; how many housing units have been built in (i) greenbelt and (ii) brownfield land in each such year; and how many hectares of (A) greenbelt and (B) brownfield land have been consumed by housing in each such year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771411","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>Responsibility for funding of the centralised National Resilience capability training delivered by the Fire Service College was transferred from the Department for Communities and Local Government to the Home Office under a Machinery of Government change effective from 1 April 2016. Home Office spend data can be found at the following link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-spending-over-25000-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-spending-over-25000-2016</a>;</p><p>This includes Capita Business Services activities who own the Fire Service College.</p><p> </p><p>DLCG also publish data at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-spending-over-250" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-spending-over-250</a></p><p> </p><p>As part of Government policy to devolve further responsibilities to the Fire sector, centralised National Resilience training was passed to the sector lead authority, Merseyside Fire and Rescue Authority, effective from 1<sup>st</sup> April 2017. This offers increased value for money and allows in-year savings made to be used for the benefit of the national resilience capabilities.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-23T17:44:38.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771411/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771411/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Fire and Rescue Services: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department spent on training delivered by the Fire Service College in (a) 2015-16, (b) 2016-17 and (c) 2017 to date; how much she expects to be spent on such training in (i) 2017-18, (ii) 2018-19 and (iii) 2019-20; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771412","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>Local authorities are responsible for setting levels of council tax. Council tax is 9.1 pre cent lower in real terms in 2017-18 than it was in 2010-11.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:16:05.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771412/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771412/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Council Tax: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effects on the number of (a) households and (b) children living in poverty of changes to council tax in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771413","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>We will work to address the challenges of social care for our ageing population, bringing forward proposals for consultation to build widespread support.</p><p>The Government will make further announcements on the scope of the consultation in due course.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-10-24T08:57:26.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771413/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771413/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-16","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Green Paper and consultation on the long-term funding for social care will include proposals for working age adults with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","107806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771414","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government have staff within the EU Exit Team leading on providing advice to Ministers on EU exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department's other priorities, it would not be possible to give an exact figure on the number of officials working on matters relating to EU Exit.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:15:46.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771414/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771414/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many officials in his Department are currently working on matters relating to the UK exiting the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771415","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-24","<p>Departmental records show the following expenditure by financial years on software licenses:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Spend (inc VAT)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£230,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£306,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£762,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>There has been significant investment in software licenses associated with the development of major business applications, in particular:</p><ul><li><p>E-Claims, which supports the administration of the European Regional Development fund and European Social Fund</p></li><li><p>DELTA, which rationalises the Department’s key data collection and grant administration systems</p></li><li><p>CORE, which collects social housing sales and lettings data</p></li><li><p>Troubled Families (TFAM), which supports a key DCLG policy helping over 400,000 families</p></li><li><p>Fair Chance Fund (FCF), which supports a £15 million programme to move the hardest to help homeless people off the streets and into employment where possible.</p></li></ul>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-24T13:59:19.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771415/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771415/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Department for Communities and Local Government: Computer Software","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department spent on software licences in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771416","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The number of principal local authorities in England that did not increase their levels of council tax in each of the last three years are shown below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/council-tax-statistics#council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/council-tax-statistics#council-tax-levels-set-by-local-authorities</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-20T14:11:43.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771416/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771416/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities in England have not increased levels of council tax in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771417","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-23T16:10:51.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771417/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771417/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Housing: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the average cost to the owner of a domestic dwelling of damage caused by fire in a property that (a) has and (b) does not have a smoke alarm.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771418","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Figures on the age of fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0503 at the link below.</p><p>Figures on the source of ignition causing fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0602 at the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","107771 ; 107798","2017-10-24T15:34:20.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771418/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771418/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Private Rented Housing: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number and proportion of domestic fires in the private rented sector in England that have occurred as a result of (a) smoking and (b) electrical faults since 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771419","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Figures on the age of fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0503 at the link below.</p><p>Figures on the source of ignition causing fire-related fatalities and non-fatal casualties, in all dwelling types, can be found in table FIRE0602 at the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","107771 ; 107797","2017-10-24T15:34:21.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771419/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771419/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Housing: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) fatalities and (b) injuries there were in England as a result of fire in (i) privately rented, (ii) social and (iii) owner-occupied homes in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771420","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Stay Well This Winter campaign is a joint campaign between NHS England and Public Health England, which aims to ease seasonal pressure on NHS urgent care and emergency services.</p><p>I have not been involved in specific discussions on this campaign. However, my department regularly engages at both official and Ministerial level across government to ensure we are prepared for winter.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-20T14:11:09.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771420/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771420/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Health Education: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent discussions he has had with cabinet colleagues on the planning of the Stay Well This Winter 2017 campaign.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771421","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We have listened to the sector through our earlier public consultation on this issue, and we have also taken careful stock of the joint DCLG/DWP Select Committee report on supported housing.</p><p>We know the supported housing sector needs certainty to help it continue to plan and deliver new much needed supported housing.</p><p>We will set out further details on our plans later in the autumn.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-20T13:19:50.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771421/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771421/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771421/answer/previousversion/16277","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish a supported housing green paper.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","107812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771422","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-23","<p>Since May 2010 the Department for Communities and Local Government has supported two pieces of research into antisemitism. In November 2010 we supported the publication of <em>Playing the Nazi</em> <em>by Card</em> by the European Institute for the Study of Contemporary Antisemitism (EISCA) which looked at antisemitic discourse. In September 2017 we supported alongside the Community Security Trust the Institute of Jewish Policy Research's (JPR) study entitled <em>Antisemitism in contemporary Great Britain: Key findings from the JPR survey of attitudes towards Jews and Israel </em>which takes an in-depth look at attitudes towards Jews and Israel among the population of Great Britain, both across society as a whole, and in key subgroups within the population, notably the far-left, the far-right, Christians and Muslims.</p><p>.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-23T16:21:17.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771422/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771422/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research his Department has (a) commissioned and (b) published on anti-Semitism since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771423","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>Earlier this year, the Government gave councils access to £9.25 billion more dedicated funding for adult social care over the next three years. This includes an additional £2 billion of funding in England, as announced at the Spring Budget 2017. One of the three purposes of this funding was to reduce pressures on the NHS, including supporting more people to be discharged from hospital when they are ready and we know local authorities are putting resources into this. However, performance is not just about money, and considerable variation remains across the country. We will be monitoring the position carefully on delayed transfers of care in the run up to winter.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-19T12:42:56.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771423/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771423/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of reductions in social care funding on the delayed transfer of care.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","107962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771424","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-26","<p>I refer the Rt Hon Member to the answer I gave to Question UIN 3273 on 10 July 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-26T13:58:11.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771424/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771424/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771424/answer/previousversion/16278","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress is being made on the roll-out of voluntary right to buy.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","107978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771425","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>Should Sheffield City Region Combined Authorities proceed to elect a Mayor with full powers, that newly elected Mayor would benefit from a range of powers devolved from central government, as well as new funding, including:</p><ul><li>£30 million a year for 30 years to invest in local strategic priorities;</li><li>Responsibility over the region’s transport budget;</li><li>Strategic planning;</li><li>Skills funding</li></ul><p>The associated cost of an election was made clear to Leaders throughout the process. We have estimated that the cost of the May 2018 mayoral election to the Sheffield City Region Combined Authority and its four constituent councils, including costs of the election booklet containing candidate information (which is required to be distributed to each elector), is likely to be in the range £1.5 million to £2 million.</p><p>An election of a mayor without powers is certainly not without benefits for Sheffield City Region, they would be a significant public figure who would both be chair of the combined authority and could take their place as the voice of the region alongside the other city region mayors in the Northern Powerhouse and in other forums with government or stakeholders.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-10-19T16:06:18.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771425/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771425/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Mayors: Sheffield City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the cost of the Sheffield City Region mayoral election.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","107979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771426","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The application for confirmation of the London Borough of Newham's proposed selective licensing designation is under consideration and a decision will be made in due course.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","108022","2017-10-20T14:22:31.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771426/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771426/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771426/answer/previousversion/16286","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Private Rented Housing: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to make a decision on the application from the London Borough of Newham to continue its private rented sector licensing scheme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","107992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771427","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-20","<p>The application for confirmation of the London Borough of Newham's proposed selective licensing designation is under consideration and a decision will be made in due course.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","107992","2017-10-20T14:22:31.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771427/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771427/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771427/answer/previousversion/16287","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","Private Rented Housing: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to make a decision on the London Borough of Newham's application to continue its private rented sector licensing scheme.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","108022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771428","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>The London Stadium is owned and managed by E20 Stadium LLP, a joint venture between the London Legacy Development Corporation (LLDC) and Newham Council. E20 Stadium LLP is responsible for the costs of the seat moves which have previously been disclosed as being estimated at circa £8 million a year.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor of London, to whom the LLDC is directly accountable, has launched an investigation into the costs and operation of the London Stadium. Further information on the stadium costs associated with hosting this year's IAAF World Championships will be available on publication of this investigation’s report by the Mayor and also as part of the standard LLDC and Greater London Authority reporting cycles.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-24T16:27:50.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771428/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771428/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","World Athletics Championships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the cost to the public purse was of converting the London Stadium to and from an athletics venue for the 2017 IAAF World Championships.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","108013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771429","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport does not collect or publish data on the number of public library closures in each Parliamentary constituency. Data relating to public libraries is collected from local authorities by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy which makes available the data annually to subscribers.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-10-19T08:37:33.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771429/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771429/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771429/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Public Libraries: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2017 to Question 106052, when the complete figures for the numbers of library closures for the last 12 months will be available; and if she will publish the data her Department holds on the numbers of libraries in each constituency in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","107956"
