"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771431","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The scope of the review and the evidence sought is outlined in the terms of reference published on gov.uk. Key partners, stakeholders and parties interested in S4C have been invited to submit evidence for the chair to consider. The chair and review secretariat welcomes evidence from anyone with an interest in S4C.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-19T12:16:25.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771431/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771431/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","S4C Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the independent review of S4C announced on 7 August 2017, whether information on (a) the deadline for submitting evidence, (b) the questions on which the review is gathering evidence and (c) the contact to whom evidence should be submitted has been made publicly available online.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","107920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771432","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Department does not hold this level of information. Think Broadband (http://labs.thinkbroadband.com/local/uk) publish up-to-date information on the percentage of premises receiving below 2 and 10 MB/s. These are currently reported as follows:</p><p>0.76% of UK premises experience download speeds below 2Mbps.</p><p>2.81% of UK premises experience download speeds of less than 10Mbps.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-24T16:07:43.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771432/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771432/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771432/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what percentage of UK premises experience broadband download speeds of less than (a) 1MB/s, (b) 2MB/s, (c) 5MB/s and (d) 10 MB/s.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","107944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771433","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-19","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer to PQ 106697.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","107960","2017-10-19T09:15:56.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771433/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771433/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771433/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Cultural Heritage: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what financial assistance the Government has given to cultural and artistic venues to assist with extra security costs incurred as a result of recent terrorist attacks in London.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","107945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771434","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>National Lottery good cause money is allocated by expert bodies at arm's length from Government, taking account of their own priorities and the need for equitable distribution.</p><p> </p><p>Policy directions are set by DCMS or the devolved administrations as relevant. The Big Lottery Fund, Heritage Lottery Fund, Arts Council England, Sport England and British Film Institute are all required to take equality of access into account in developing programmes and considering grant allocations. This requirement does not apply to UK Sport's as their funding targets elite athletes.</p><p> </p><p>Each distributor takes account of a variety of considerations including geographical spread of funding, deprivation data and participation rates when determining priorities and allocating budget. Distributors run specific programmes designed to encourage applications from less well-represented areas.</p><p> </p><p>Information on projects in receipt of a Lottery award can be found on the National Lottery Grants Database at the following link: http://www.lottery.culture.gov.uk and from Lottery Distributors' own websites. The grants database can be sorted on a national, regional, local authority and constituency level.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-24T13:52:36.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771434/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771434/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771434/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","National Lottery: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an assessment of the equity of regional and national trends in the award of National Lottery grants over the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","107899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771435","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>At Autumn Statement 2016, the Government announced a a £1.1bn package to boost the UK’s digital infrastructure. This sum is intended to cover all future connectivity technologies and cover work in this area until 2020-21. This included investment in a nationally coordinated programme of full fibre and 5G Testbed &amp; Trials.</p><p>To date, the Government has invested £16 million for three leading 5G research institutions to establish a test network to test and trial 5G technologies and applications. This week, a £25 million competition was announced to select projects for initial funding as part of the first Phase of the Testbeds &amp; Trials Programme.</p><p>For the Local Full Fibre (LFFN) Programme, the Government announced in September that £10 million has been allocated for 6 full fibre test projects around the country, in Aberdeen and Aberdeenshire, West Sussex, Coventry and Warwickshire, Bristol (with Bath and North East Somerset), West Yorkshire and Greater Manchester. Further measures will be set out in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-25T09:19:40.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771435/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771435/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771435/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","5G","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, on what the £740 million 5G research and infrastructure fund announced in the 2016 Autumn Statement has been spent.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","107884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771436","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>We hope to make an announcement on the Government’s Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures shortly.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-10-24T11:10:03.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771436/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771436/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771436/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish the recommendations on fixed-odds betting terminals of the Responsible Gambling Strategy Board and the Gambling Commission.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","107900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771437","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-25","<p>For exit payments in 2016-17, £151,325.36 was paid to women and £110,906.82 was paid to men.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-25T08:43:11.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771437/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771437/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2017 to Question 105517, on Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: redundancy pay, what the total amount was that was paid to (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","107894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771438","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>Ministers support a large number of events in the DCMS sectors and meet many representatives from those sectors, the specific attendees at events attended to by ministers is not centrally held.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-24T16:10:53.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771438/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771438/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Government's publication Ministerial hospitality, 1 April to 30 June 2017, published on 13 October 2017, whether (a) representatives or employees of the firm which offered that hospitality and (b) lobbyists or contractors of those firms were present at those events.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","107871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771439","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The department is engaged in ongoing discussions with the Treasury regarding all new spending proposals.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-10-19T09:41:49.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771439/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771439/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-16","Cultural Heritage: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on providing finance for the establishment of a Cultural Development Fund.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","108027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771440","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Defence Estate Optimisation Programme takes a long-term portfolio approach to transforming the Defence Estate into one fit for the future military needs of the Armed Forces.</p><p>Taken as a whole the programme is proven to provide value for money by using the receipts from disposal sites and other allocated funding to enable new investment into the Ministry of Defence retained core estate. This will then deliver enduring efficiencies in infrastructure operating costs.</p><p>Initial assessments into relocating the units presently based in Strensall to Gamecock Barracks are being undertaken with the costs considered as part of the whole programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-24T16:10:42.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771440/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771440/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Gamecock Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the financial implications of re-deploying military units from Strensall to Gamecock Barracks, Nuneaton.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","107880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771441","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not analyse the locations where recruits to the UK Armed Forces have been recruited from.</p><p>As part of the recruitment process an individual can declare more than one postcode e.g. 'home', 'work' or 'other'.</p><p>Any declared 'home' location may not reflect where that person is from.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-19T16:31:43.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771441/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771441/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons his Department does not record the postcode of new recruits to HM Armed Forces.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","107912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771442","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-23","<p>Since November 2014, 61 acres of invasive acacia have been removed from the Special Area of Conservation and land managed by the Ministry of Defence at Cape Pyla, an open area of countryside affected by illegal bird trapping. Birdlife Cyprus has undertaken assessments of bird trapping across the whole of Cyprus, including the Sovereign Base Areas (SBA); but they have not yet published any specific data associated with the removal of this acacia at Cape Pyla. Their next set of estimates will be issued early in 2018 after the present migration season has ended.</p><p>The SBA Police have separately assessed that up to 40 trappers planted and exploited this acacia at Cape Pyla and, using the Birdlife Cyprus methodology, together with a combination of other measures to counter bird trapping, is resulting in significant numbers of birds being saved. Preliminary assessments from the SBA Police, and noted by various Non-Government Organisations, indicate that bird trapping activity so far during the 2017 autumn migration is lower than in previous years.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-23T16:24:17.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771442/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771442/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Cyprus: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the effects of acacia clearances in the UK Sovereign Base Area in Cyprus on the illegal trapping of songbirds on the base.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","107794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771443","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-19","<p>There have been no discussions in relation to the ambassadorial use of HMS DUNCAN by Belfast City Council or Invest Northern Ireland.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-19T14:27:14.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771443/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771443/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","HMS Duncan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the ambassadorial use of HMS Duncan by Belfast City Council or Invest NI.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","107811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771444","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-23","<p>Our refreshed defence industrial policy will further explain how our investment choices take account of factors contributing to a more dynamic and productive economy, in which the UK defence supply chain plays a crucial part.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-23T16:18:23.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771444/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771444/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that the planned refresh of the Government's defence industrial policy ensures that the flow of work from prime contractors to UK-based sub-contractors is measured in order to compare and evaluate the relative merits of competing proposals to meet his Department's requirements.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bowie","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Andrew Bowie","107849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771445","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Hawk T1 aircraft is due to remain in service until 2030. It is currently used by 100 Squadron and 736 Naval Air Squadron for operational training, as well as by the Red Arrows and the RAF Centre of Aviation Medicine. The UK currently has a pool of 75 T1 aircraft from which the Red Arrows and those other units are able to draw. In addition 28 Hawk T2 aircraft are used in a flying training role. Given the number of aircraft currently in service there is no pressing need to make a decision on Red Arrows replacement.</p><p>Those aircraft providing operational training are planned be replaced from 2027 by the Air Support to Defence Operational Training (ASDOT) programme which is still in the development stage. The nature of fleet management means that although some of the remaining units will incrementally drawdown earlier, sufficient Hawk T1 aircraft will be retained in the pool of available aircraft to support the requirements of the final units until replacement. Consideration will be given to replacing the Hawk T1 with the Red Arrows in due course, but a decision is unlikely to be taken until after the end of this Parliament.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","107748 ; 107757 ; 107758","2017-10-23T16:16:59.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771445/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771445/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will ensure that the Royal Air Force Aeronautics Team always flies in aircraft manufactured in the UK.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","107787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771446","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Ministry of Defence is working closely with the defence industry and other Government Departments to understand the implications and opportunities presented by the UK's departure from the European Union.</p><p>The European defence sector is already closely integrated; leading companies have a presence right across Europe, and across the UK, including the North West. It is worth noting that current major European collaborative capability projects, such as the Typhoon programme, are managed bilaterally or with groups of partners, rather than through the EU.</p><p>Through our future partnership with the European Union, we want to explore how best to ensure that our industries can continue working together to deliver the capabilities that we need to protect the UK and its allies and partners.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-19T16:31:00.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771446/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771446/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Defence and Aerospace Industry: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on defence and aerospace manufacturing capability in the North West of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","107966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771447","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-23","<p>In the National Security through Technology White Paper 2012 (Cm8278) the Government committed to take action to protect our freedom of action and operational advantage where essential for national security. The White Paper describes four general cases in which this is most likely to apply, with examples, including aspects of cryptographic production, deployment and support, and weapons and propulsion systems for the UK's nuclear deterrent. We do not comment on the precise circumstances or aspects of capabilities we might regard as critical on national security grounds.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-23T16:08:10.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771447/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771447/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which defence systems and equipment his Department regards as critical for retaining sovereign defence capability.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","107999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771448","Department for Education","false","2017-10-24","<p>The priorities and targets for the Norwich Opportunity Area were developed and agreed by the Opportunity Area Partnership Board. The board is made up of key local stakeholders, including representatives from education and business. The Partnership Board conducted a comprehensive, in-depth analysis of local needs and set out its four key priorities and targets on the basis of the evidence and local consultation.</p><p>I strongly agree about the importance of encouraging more disadvantaged young people, and indeed more young people from all backgrounds, to take up high quality vocational qualifications. One of the priorities set out in the Norwich Opportunity Area plan is to ensure that young people have access to the information and support they need to move successfully between education and into work. Within this priority, the plan has set an ambitious target around increasing the number of young people going into either a higher apprenticeship or higher education. The plan also sets the target that by 2021, 50% of 19 year olds will be qualified to level 3, which includes vocational qualifications. We will keep these priorities under review as the Opportunity Area programme develops and would be happy to engage with the hon. Member on next steps.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-24T15:51:01.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771448/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771448/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Young People: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reason the Norwich Area Programme targets do not recognise vocational trade-related qualifications as a measure of progress for disadvantaged young people.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","108014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771449","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>I am sorry, but the proportion of eligible three and four year old children in England who are not claiming the early years pupil premium is not held by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-19T16:18:40.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771449/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771449/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Pre-school Education: Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of eligible three and four year-olds in England are not claiming the early years pupil premium.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","107967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771450","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>I am sorry but we do not currently hold data on how many parents are accessing 30 hours of free childcare with multiple providers at a national level but this will be captured in the 2018 census.</p><p>However, our recently published independent evaluation of the early delivery programme shows parents are prepared to use multiple providers, with around 18% of children using multiple providers in three of the four early rollout areas. In early implementation, the report found that around one in five children used two providers for the free entitlement hours but the use of three or more providers was rare.</p><p>The full reports are available here:</p><ul><li><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-rollout-of-30-hours-free-childcare-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-rollout-of-30-hours-free-childcare-evaluation</a>.</li><li><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-free-childcare-early-implementation-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-free-childcare-early-implementation-evaluation</a>.</li></ul><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-19T16:15:02.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771450/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771450/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Children and Families of 12 October 2017, Official Report, column 212WH, in how many instances parents are using 30 hours of free childcare with (a) one provider, (b) two providers and (c) more that two providers.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","107955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771451","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>Spending by levy-paying employers and non-levy paying employers on apprenticeship training and assessment depends on demand for, and cost of, apprenticeships that employers themselves choose.</p><p> </p><p>In England, employers who pay the levy can use funds in their apprenticeship service accounts to pay for training and assessment. Funds enter employers’ accounts every month based on the amount of Apprenticeship Levy declared, the proportion of their pay to employees living in England and a 10% top-up applied from Government.</p><p> </p><p>For non-levy paying employers, government funding is awarded to training providers under contract. We launched a procurement at the end of July which closed in early September. Through this procurement exercise, the Education and Skills Funding Agency will make available at least £440m of funding over 15 months for new apprenticeship starts from 1 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>By 2019-20 funding available for apprenticeships in England will be £2.45 billion; double what was spent in 2010-11.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","107964","2017-10-19T15:44:04.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771451/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771451/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of the revenue raised by the Apprenticeship Levy will be allocated to fund apprenticeships with non-levy employers.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","107963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771452","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>Spending by levy-paying employers and non-levy paying employers on apprenticeship training and assessment depends on demand for, and cost of, apprenticeships that employers themselves choose.</p><p> </p><p>In England, employers who pay the levy can use funds in their apprenticeship service accounts to pay for training and assessment. Funds enter employers’ accounts every month based on the amount of Apprenticeship Levy declared, the proportion of their pay to employees living in England and a 10% top-up applied from Government.</p><p> </p><p>For non-levy paying employers, government funding is awarded to training providers under contract. We launched a procurement at the end of July which closed in early September. Through this procurement exercise, the Education and Skills Funding Agency will make available at least £440m of funding over 15 months for new apprenticeship starts from 1 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>By 2019-20 funding available for apprenticeships in England will be £2.45 billion; double what was spent in 2010-11.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","107963","2017-10-19T15:44:04.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771452/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771452/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of the total money raised by the Apprenticeship Levy will be allocated to levy-paying companies for their own apprenticeship training schemes.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","107964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771453","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>We have not undertaken an assessment of this type. We continue to monitor closely the impact of the apprenticeship funding reforms introduced in May 2017 on employers and providers.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-19T15:49:52.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771453/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771453/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what comparative assessment she has made of registered training providers in receipt of (a) less, (b) the same, (c) more funding in real terms per apprenticeship start in the period (i) May to December 2017 and (ii) August 2016 to April 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","107965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771454","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>Our intended funding for apprenticeships was published in the skills funding letter in March 2017 – <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/599089/SFA_Letter_2017-18_final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/599089/SFA_Letter_2017-18_final.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>This includes a breakdown of intended funding for 16-18 year olds. Actual spend will depend on the demand and cost of apprenticeships that employers choose.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1 April 2017, apprenticeships are funded entirely from the Apprenticeship Levy.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-19T15:35:59.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771454/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771454/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department's budget is for apprenticeships for 16 to 18 year olds in (a) 2017-18 and (b) 2018-19; and what proportion of that budget is generated by the Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","107917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771455","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Department for Education does not hold information relating to the number of people that are eligible for 30 hours free childcare based on a job offer.</p><p> </p><p>On the 17 July 2017, the Department for Education published an evaluation of the eight local authority areas that took part in the early innovators programme for 30 hours free childcare.</p><p>In the Early Implementer areas, almost a quarter (23%) of mothers and almost one in ten (9%) fathers increased their work hours as a result of the extended childcare offer. This effect was notably stronger for families with relatively lower incomes. The full evaluation can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-free-childcare-early-implementation-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/30-hours-free-childcare-early-implementation-evaluation</a>.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-19T16:36:14.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771455/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771455/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Children and Families of 12 October 2017, Official Report, column 210WH, how many times a validation code has been generated on the basis of a job offer.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","107954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771456","Department for Education","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Education and Skills Fuding Agency publish allocations annually and update them throughout the year. Allocations for the 2016 to 2017 funding year can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sfa-funding-allocations-to-training-providers-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Non-levy apprenticeship allocations for May to December 2017 will be published in November 2017.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-19T15:40:31.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771456/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771456/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish a list of the funding allocated to each training provider for apprenticeship starts for the periods (a) August 2016 to April 2017 and (b) May to December 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","107918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771457","Department for Education","false","2017-10-23","<p>Figures on the number and proportion of children taking a free school meal and those eligible for free school meals are published, for all authorities in England, annually. The figures can be found in the statistical first releases available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a>.</p><p>Data are not summarised by parliamentary constituency, but data for each school is available via the link to underlying tables then the file ‘…Schools_Pupils_UD’. The figures can be filtered by school phase and parliamentary constituency.</p><p>A UK figure is not available. As education is a devolved matter, statistics on schools are published separately by the four administrations.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","108047","2017-10-23T15:00:18.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771457/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771457/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-16","Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of those eligible for free school meals in (a) Enfield North constituency, (b) London and (c) the UK took up free school meals in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","108046"
