"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771598","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Department for Transport has not made a specific assessment of the age of tyres fitted to vehicles involved in collisions. Official statistics indicate where, in the opinion of the attending police officer, a tyre was illegal, defective or under inflated and may have contributed to the accident. In 2014, 2015 and 2016 there were respectively 714, 598 and 550 collisions where tyres were considered to be a contributory factor.</p><p>The Department first issued guidance in 2013, which was subsequently updated, most recently in October 2016, recommending tyres over 10 years old should not be fitted to front steering axles, but only at the rear on twin wheels. A year after the guidance was published, a further survey of older PSVs was carried out by DVSA. This survey indicated a reduction in the average age of tyres fitted in the PSV fleet and demonstrated widespread compliance with the advice.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-24T16:39:23.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771598/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771598/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the number of vehicle accidents in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016 that involved vehicles with tyres over 10 years old.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","108059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771599","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>All flights from Ercan to the UK are subject to additional passenger screening at the departure gate in Turkey. We believe these are necessary measures, especially given aviation remains a systemic target for terrorists, and those with malicious intent. We work with our international partners on aviation security, and keep measures under constant review.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-19T09:51:55.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771599/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771599/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Airports: Northern Cyprus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will review the decision to increase security requirements on passengers flying between Ercan International Airport and UK airports.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","107831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771600","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-24","<p>Highways England currently has a £15m programme to roll out rapid chargepoints at least every 20 miles along 95% of the strategic road network. As part of the Autumn Statement 2016, a further £80m was made available for electric vehicle charging infrastructure. The Government intends to set out its plans for this funding as part of the Zero Emission Road Transport Strategy due to be published by March 2018.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-24T14:29:47.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771600/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771600/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Electric Vehicles: Peterlee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will provide funding for the installation of an electric vehicle rapid-charging point in Peterlee.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","107857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771601","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Office for Low Emission Vehicles has a number of schemes in place to support the installation of electric vehicle chargepoints across the UK. The Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme provides a grant of up to £500 to install chargepoints at domestic properties with access to offstreet parking. The Workplace charging scheme is available to businesses, charities, and public sector organisations to install chargepoints for their employees and fleets. A grant of £300 for each socket is available, up to a maximum of 20. Local authorities can apply for the Onstreet Residential Chargepoint Scheme which provides grant funding to install onstreet chargepoints for local residents that lack access to off-street parking, up to a maximum of £7,500 per chargepoint.</p><p> </p><p>The Automated and Electric Vehicles Bill, introduced on 18 October, includes powers to expand deployment of electric vehicle infrastructure across the UK, with requirements for provision at motorway service areas and large fuel retailers.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-24T15:38:59.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771601/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771601/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Electric Vehicles: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the number of electric vehicle charging points in the Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","107858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771602","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>Since 2014 Access for All has completed 30 projects and another 7 are currently on site. A further 28 are due to start construction before 2019.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-19T09:53:05.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771602/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771602/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Railway Stations: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many station upgrades are due to start before April 2019 under the Network Rail Access for All scheme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","107813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771603","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The spend on Access for All projects is recorded by Network Rail route and the cost of work done to date since 2014 is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Anglia £11.872m</p><p>East Midlands £1.184m</p><p>London North East £20.599m</p><p>London North West £15.476m</p><p>Scotland £13.112m</p><p>Sussex £2.196m</p><p>Wales £6.387m</p><p>Wessex £12.828m</p><p>Western £5.583m</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-19T12:29:20.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771603/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771603/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Railway Stations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent on improving the accessibility of train stations for disabled people under Network Rail's Access for All scheme since 2014 in each region.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","107818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771604","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>No schemes under Access for All have been cancelled during Control Period 5. The construction of 26 stations has been deferred to Control Period 6 and these stations are in the following regions:</p><p> </p><p>North West 1</p><p>North East 2</p><p>East 3</p><p>East Midlands 2</p><p>West Midlands 1</p><p>Wales 4</p><p>West 1</p><p>London 9</p><p>South East 3</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-19T12:33:50.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771604/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771604/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Railway Stations: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many planned station upgrades under Network Rail's Access for All scheme have been (a) cancelled during rail control period 5 and (b) deferred to rail control period in each region.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","107817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771605","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-23","<p>I have discussed this matter with the Aviation Health Unit within the Medical Department of the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) as part of their wider role as specialist adviser to the Government on aviation health issues.</p><p> </p><p>The deployment of airline staff is an operational matter for airlines, but I would urge them to take account of WHO guidance and FCO travel advice when making these decisions.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-23T11:26:24.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771605/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771605/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Aviation: Zika Virus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make representations to representatives of the airline sector on the withdrawal of the Zika list for cabin crew who are pregnant or trying to conceive when travelling to countries with that virus.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","107807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771606","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Government has no plans to restrict lorries to the inside lane of motorways.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-23T11:22:30.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771606/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771606/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Motorways: Large Goods Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to restrict lorries to the inside lane of motorways only; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","107783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771607","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-20","<p>The National Networks National Policy Statement (NN-NPS) sets out Government’s policy for Strategic Rail Freight Interchange (SRFI) development. It states the importance of SRFIs being located near the business markets they will serve – major urban centres, or groups of centres. The NN-NPS states that to facilitate modal shift from road to rail, a network of SRFIs is needed across the regions to serve regional, sub-regional and cross-regional markets with good connectivity with both the road and strategic rail freight network.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-20T09:27:54.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771607/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771607/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he plans to take to ensure that new rail freight terminals are appropriately sited to benefit the national economy.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","107792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771608","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-23","<p>Users of mobility scooters and powered wheelchairs are not required to take out compulsory third-party insurance cover. However, the Government recommends that users take out a third-party insurance policy.</p><p> </p><p>A compulsory insurance regime has the potential to penalize older or disabled people unfairly. There is currently no reliable evidence to show that the use of mobility vehicles creates a major public safety issue.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-23T11:01:16.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771608/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771608/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Invalid Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's response to its consultation on proposed changes to the laws governing powered mobility scooters, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing compulsory third-party insurance cover; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne","108081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771609","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-24","<p>Lead responsibility for managing surface water flood risks lies with Lead Local Flood Authorities (LLFAs).</p><p> </p><p>The Government, through Defra, provides the majority of funding for flood and coastal erosion risk management activities for England in the form of Grant in Aid which is administered by the Environment Agency. As well as using their own funds, LLFAs can bid for this funding to carry out surface water management projects. Funding for projects to reduce the risk of surface water flooding is considered on the same criteria as other flood and coastal erosion risks. Projects which have the greatest economic benefits, which provide protection to the most homes in relation to their cost, and those that protect the environment are prioritised for funding. In the six year programme from 2015 to 2021, £767,000 of this funding was allocated to surface water flood risk management schemes in Norfolk.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government also provides funding through the Local Government Settlement to LLFAs to carry out their surface water management and other duties under the Flood and Water Management Act 2010. The total amount and breakdown per authority is published on gov.uk[1]. The total of the LLFA entries for Norfolk for 2017-18 is £851,730. This shows the significance central government gives to these services, but local authorities have freedom to determine their own priorities.</p><p> </p><p>[1] https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/core-spending-power-visible-lines-of-funding-2017-to-2018</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","107923","2017-10-24T13:45:20.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771609/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771609/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-16","Flood Control: Norfolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of funding to protect domestic dwellings and business from surface water flooding has been awarded to Norfolk.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","107930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771610","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Department plans to publish the guidance this autumn.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-19T09:49:45.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771610/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771610/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to publish the detailed legislative guidance on the franchising powers made available to combined authorities with elected mayors under the provisions of the Bus Services Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","107957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771611","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Department has published guidance for local authorities and practitioners on designing shared space schemes in Local Transport Note 1/11: Shared Space.</p><p> </p><p>To inform the advice given in the Local Transport Note, the Department commissioned an extensive research project in 2010, more information on which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/shared-space" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/shared-space</a>. This included qualitative research with a number of different road user types: visually impaired pedestrians; mobility impaired pedestrians; pedestrians with learning difficulties; pedestrians who are deaf or hard of hearing; non-disabled pedestrians; and drivers.</p><p> </p><p>We have been working with the Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation, which has been carrying out a review of 12 shared space and other street design schemes. This will report soon, and provide recommendations for further work in this area.</p><p> </p><p>The draft Accessibility Action Plan, currently out for consultation, includes an action for us to consider CIHT’s recommendations, when received, and how to take them forward, by the end of 2017.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-19T09:54:39.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771611/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771611/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-16","Shared Spaces: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made on the effect of shared-space schemes on disabled people.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","107968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771612","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government has committed to use European Structural Funds money that comes back to the UK following departure from the EU to create a United Kingdom Shared Prosperity Fund. We will set out a timetable for its development in due course.</p><p>The guarantee announced by my Rt Hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer is also giving all parts of the UK funding certainty.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-10-19T15:59:38.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771612/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771612/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-16","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 11 October 2017 to Question 105962, what the timetable is for the establishment of the Shared Property Fund; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","107953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771613","Wales Office","false","2017-10-19","<p>My ministerial colleagues and I regularly meet with stakeholders across Wales, including discussing with representatives of business, the third sector and universities how funding for growth across the UK can best be designed and delivered after we leave the European Union. Since the referendum result in June 2016, the impact on Wales of the UK leaving the EU has been a standing agenda item.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-10-19T13:06:34.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771613/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771613/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-10-16","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many meetings he has had with organisations and campaigners from Wales since June 2016 on European Structural Investment Funds after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","108026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771614","Wales Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>In 2016, 8.5% of all goods exported from Wales went to the Middle East. Figures for service exports are not yet available for 2016. In 2015, 14.2% of all services exported from Wales went to Asia, which is where the Office for National Statistics (ONS) categorises Middle Eastern countries in its service exports release. The ONS does not publish data detailing what percentage of the service exports that are sent to Asia go specifically to the Middle East.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-10-23T13:20:59.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771614/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771614/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-10-16","Exports: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of total Welsh exports in (a) goods and (b) services went to the Middle East in 2016.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","108060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771615","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-24","<p>Currently plans are not sufficiently mature to provide dates for either of these proposed moves.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-24T15:14:24.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771615/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771615/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-16","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 11 October 2017 to Question 105109, when he plans for (a) the light infantry unit to move to St Athan and (b) No. 4 School of Technical Training at St Athan to leave; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","107893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771616","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-24","<p>In 2015, the Government published guidance for employers and service providers on how to specifically support and include transgender people at work. This helps them to meet their obligations under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p>We also recently issued instructions to offender management services to improve the treatment and management of transgender offenders. The new guidelines state that all transgender prisoners must be allowed to express the gender with which they identify.</p><p> </p><p>Our National lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) Survey has recently closed and we will use the data we collected from this to help to identify areas that service provision needs to improve for LGBT people.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-24T16:42:28.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771616/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771616/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-16","LGBT People: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 901069, whether the Government has plans to develop and implement best practice guidelines to ensure local providers account for sexual-gender identity within service provision.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Gerard Killen","107895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771617","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Government has set out in its Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy published in March 2016 that it is committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution, and believes that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to find routes out.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office has committed £150,000 to commission research into the nature and prevalence of prostitution in England and Wales. We believe that such an evidence base is vital prior to considering further changes to policy or legislation.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided £389,000 to organisations which help those who want to leave prostitution and sex work. Merseyside PCC have also been awarded £650,000 from the VAWG Transformation Fund to provide a victim-focused service for sex workers who are victims, or at risk of sexual or domestic violence and abuse, exploitation or human trafficking.</p><p> </p><p>We know that issues around prostitution are complex, and can impact on individuals in different ways. Local areas and police forces are in the best position to identify and respond to these issues, and are able to adapt their approach to take account of such complexities. They are supported in this by guidance developed by the National Policing Lead for prostitution.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","107789","2017-10-24T16:46:32.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771617/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771617/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to adopt a strategy on prostitution which emphasises preventing women and girls entering prostitution and support women wishing to exit prostitution; what steps she plans to take to ensure that women are not penalised by the implementation of such a strategy; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","107788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771618","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Government has set out in its Violence Against Women and Girls Strategy published in March 2016 that it is committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution, and believes that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to find routes out.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office has committed £150,000 to commission research into the nature and prevalence of prostitution in England and Wales. We believe that such an evidence base is vital prior to considering further changes to policy or legislation.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided £389,000 to organisations which help those who want to leave prostitution and sex work. Merseyside PCC have also been awarded £650,000 from the VAWG Transformation Fund to provide a victim-focused service for sex workers who are victims, or at risk of sexual or domestic violence and abuse, exploitation or human trafficking.</p><p> </p><p>We know that issues around prostitution are complex, and can impact on individuals in different ways. Local areas and police forces are in the best position to identify and respond to these issues, and are able to adapt their approach to take account of such complexities. They are supported in this by guidance developed by the National Policing Lead for prostitution.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","107788","2017-10-24T16:46:32.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771618/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771618/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-16","Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to fund specialist services to prevent women entering prostitution.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","107789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771619","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-24","<p>We announced on 23 July that we will be consulting on changes to the Gender Recognition Act. We are currently considering what the content of the consultation will be and we will make an announcement shortly.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-24T16:39:48.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771619/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771619/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-16","Gender Recognition Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, when the consultation on changes to the Gender Recognition Act 2004 will begin.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","107933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771620","Women and Equalities","false","2017-10-19","<p>In the 2017 general election 208 women were elected Members of Parliament, an increase of almost 9% from 191 women at the 2015 election. The government agrees we would like to see more women elected so that Parliament can more accurately represent the diverse British public that it serves.</p><p> </p><p>The government is looking at ways to support political parties to increase the numbers of women Parliamentary and local council candidates, including with guidance and academic research.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-10-19T16:39:41.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771620/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771620/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-10-16","Members: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what recent assessment she has made of trends in the level of female hon. Members; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","107977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771621","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-23","<p>There are no plans to meet with representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This matter has been comprehensively debated on many occasions in Parliament. The Government will not be making changes to its policy on state pension age for women born in the 1950s.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-10-23T15:54:52.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771621/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771621/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-16","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet the hon. Member for Glasgow East and a delegation from WASPI Glasgow and Lanarkshire to discuss changes to the state pension age for women born in the 1950s.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","108001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771622","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-20","<p>As at 18 October 2017, the Independent Case Examiner’s Office were allocating dedicated Investigation Case Managers:</p><ul><li>Disability, Pensions, Working Age and Debt Management complaints that were accepted on or after 22 August 2016;</li><li>Providers complaints that were accepted on or after 22 August 2016;</li><li>Child Maintenance Group complaints that were accepted on of after 11 October 2016; and</li><li>WASPI complaints that were accepted on or after 16 March 2017.</li></ul>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-20T13:45:13.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771622/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771622/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-16","Independent Case Examiner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, from what acceptance date the Independent Case Examiner's Office is allocating complaints to an investigation case manager.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","108015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771623","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-19","<p>As announced by the Secretary of State at the Work and Pensions Select Committee on 18 October 2017, DWP plans to change the Universal Credit helpline to a freephone number over the next month.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","107750","2017-10-19T14:07:33.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771623/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/771623/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-16","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of February 2016 to Question 25760, what advice he gives to applicants needing to make a telephone call to discuss their Universal Credit claim but not able to afford to use his Department's helpline.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","107919"
